  "prompt": "The club has 37 members, 20 of whom are women and 17 of whom are men. The club needs to form a 4 person party-planning committee. How many committees are possible if the committee must have 2 women and 2 men?",
  "response": "To solve this problem, we need to calculate the number of ways to select 2 women and 2 men from the club's membership.\n\nFirst, we calculate the number of ways to choose 2 women from the 20 available. This is done using the binomial coefficient:\n\n\\[\n\\binom{n}{k} = \\frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}\n\\]\n\nFor choosing 2 women out of 20, we have:\n\n\\[\n\\binom{20}{2} = \\frac{20!}{2!(20-2)!} = \\frac{20 \\times 19}{2 \\times 1} = \\frac{380}{2} = 190\n\\]\n\nNext, we calculate the number of ways to choose 2 men from the 17 available:\n\n\\[\n\\binom{17}{2} = \\frac{17!}{2!(17-2)!} = \\frac{17 \\times 16}{2 \\times 1} = \\frac{272}{2} = 136\n\\]\n\nNow, to find the total number of committees that can be formed with 2 women and 2 men, we multiply the number of ways to choose the women by the number of ways to choose the men:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Total committees} = \\binom{20}{2} \\times \\binom{17}{2} = 190 \\times 136\n\\]\n\nNow we can perform the multiplication:\n\n\\[\n190 \\times 136 = 190 \\times (100 + 36) = 19000 + 6840 = 25840\n\\]\n\nThus, the total number of possible committees with 2 women and 2 men is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{25840}\n\\]",
